            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 72-year-old retired mechanical engineer from Brno, Czech Republic. He is a stocky man of medium height, appearing somewhat pale and fatigued during consultation. He reports a two-month history of alternating bowel habits — some days diarrhoea, other days near-constipation — along with a persistent dull, bruised feeling in the lower abdomen [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:7]. He also describes occasional bright red blood mixed in his stool, which he initially attributed to haemorrhoids. Over the past six weeks he has noticed unintentional weight loss of approximately 5 kg and increasing fatigue that limits his daily walks.\n\n{patientName} lives with his wife in a ground-floor flat in the Královo Pole district of Brno. He is a keen woodworker and spent decades building furniture in his garage workshop. He enjoys watching ice hockey on television, tending a small vegetable patch on weekends, and meeting old colleagues for coffee. He smoked 15 cigarettes per day for 30 years but quit at age 58. He drinks one or two beers most evenings. His diet has historically been heavy in red meat and processed foods, with limited fibre intake.\n\nHis social support is strong — a devoted wife, two adult children, and a close circle of retired friends. He is generally stoic about health complaints and delayed seeking medical attention for the bowel symptoms for nearly three months, which is consistent with the delayed presentation pattern seen in older male patients."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b6e004df-0913-4ffc-a76f-b3006b7d97fb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a background of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed at age 64, managed with oral metformin. He also carries diagnoses of arterial hypertension (controlled with ramipril) and hyperlipidaemia (treated with atorvastatin). He takes low-dose aspirin for secondary cardiovascular prevention following a mild ischaemic event five years ago. He underwent laparoscopic cholecystectomy for symptomatic gallstones approximately eight years ago without complications. A colonoscopy performed four years ago revealed two small tubular adenomas that were resected; follow-up was recommended in three years but was not completed [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:7]. {patientName} has a 30 pack-year smoking history (quit at 58) and moderate regular alcohol use. His father died of colorectal cancer at age 69, making his family history a notable risk factor. BMI is 27.4 kg/m². He has no known prior hospitalisation for gastrointestinal malignancy."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
